{
  "text": "Thermal dissociation (which includes the first two triggers listed above) is not a viable mechanism for releasing~200 Gt C to the atmosphere. As discussed above, this quantity is equivalent to the total quantity of hydrate-derived carbon that could potentially have been released during equilibration of the sediment geothermal gradient to the peak PETM deep/intermediate ocean temperatures. This equilibration would require~3000 years [CITATION_1] ), but instead, it appears that the increase in deep/intermediate ocean temperatures (at depths where methane hydrate would have existed) lagged the initial carbon cycle perturbation by several thousand years [CITATION_2] . Moreover, thermal dissociation would result in release of methane to the water column above the depth of hydrate stability and an empirical study has shown that in such a case, most of the methane will be dissolved and oxidized in the deep ocean [CITATION_3] , buffering its effect on surface ocean/atmosphere y 13 C values. Catastrophic slope failure (the third proposed trigger) is a more viable mechanism for rapid addition of carbon from methane hydrates to the atmosphere, since in this case, the methane would be released into the water column below the depth of hydrate stability (e.g., [CITATION_4] and would escape sequestration in authigenic carbonates precipitated within the sediment [CITATION_5] . The 200 Gt of carbon required to account for the full atmosphere/surface-ocean shift is large, however, given that only~35 Gt C is present as methane hydrate or gas in the 26,000-km 2 area of the Blake Ridge, a region thought to be relatively hydrate rich. Slope failure would have had to occur over an extended area; although [CITATION_6] presented evidence that this may in fact have happened, slope failure over such an extended region within a very short (b 1 k.y.) period would require a high-energy trigger.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "17650861",
    "[CITATION_2]": "1404739",
    "[CITATION_3]": "37367416",
